etoric Is Brilliant but Secondary -- t2. Is Reality Abstract or Worldly? Or Both? -- t3. Truth Is “Truer Than Truth Itself” (The Stoic Unitary Both/And) -- t4. Highest Piety Is Unitarily Two-Dimensional -- t5. Why Is Folly Silent Regarding the Foundation of Her Thinking? -- tPART VI. Utopian Philosophy, 1516: Epicureanism within a Stoic Honestum/Utile Frame -- t1. Moral Philosophy -- t2. Stoic Corrections of Epicureans: Religious Absolutes -- t3. Stoic Corrections of Epicureans: Moral Absolutes -- t4. Stoic Utile Expanded -- t5. Stoic Justice Expanded -- t6. Corollaries -- tPART VII. Utopian Warfare: A Unitary Two-Dimensional Mindset -- t1. Super Machiavellians? -- t2. “Utter Loathing of War” and Yet a Thoroughly Militarized State -- t3. Righteous Cunning, Stratagem, and Ferocity -- t4. Beyond Machiavelli, a Seamless Mindset: Embryonic Soldiers of Christ -- tPART VIII. What Wiseman Hythloday Did Not Understand -- tCONCLUSION -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore Utopia demonstrates that Thomas More’s Utopia (1516) is not, as is widely accepted, a rhetorical play of spirit but is instead built from a particular philosophy. That philosophy was not Platonism, but classical Stoicism. Deeply disturbed in his youth by the conviction that he needed to decide between a worldly and a monastic path, Thomas More’s outlook was transformed in 1504 by Erasmus’ De taedio Iesu and Enchiridion. As a consequence, he married in 1505 and wholeheartedly committed himself to worldly affairs. His Lucian (1506), written after working directly with Erasmus, adopts the Stoic mindset; Erasmus’ Praise of Folly (1511) shows from beginning to end the workings of More’s life-changing Stoic outlook. More’s Utopia then goes on to systematically illustrate the Stoic unitary two-dimensional frame of thought within an imaginary New World setting. Before Utopia is not just a book about Thomas More. It is a book about intellectual history and the movement of ideas from the ancient world to the Renaissance. Ross Dealy emphasizes the continuity between Erasmus and More in their religious and philosophical thought, and above all the decisive influence of Erasmus on More.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aCicero.  aDesiderius Erasmus.  aEnchiridion.  aLucian.  aRenaissance.  aSeneca.  aStoicism.  aThe Praise of Folly.  aThomas More.  aUtopia.  ahistoryof literature.  aintellectual history.  aphilosophy.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP Pilot eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753448640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487534486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487534486.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  UTP Pilot eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020